As Ri resumed North Korea's already known complaints about Washington's resistance to "gradual" denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as had happened with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to "denuclearize" the Korean peninsula while Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted loosening tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the pressure through sanctions to achieve its coercive eight goal, and even opposes the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is an impossible dream, for those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions sharpen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If the other part of this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached a dead end.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly it was inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after “evil President” Trump called Kim “a man rocket on a suicide mission.”
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in taking steps to disarm, but said there was still much work to be done and that sanctions should be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
